President Joe Biden proclaims June 19, 2023, as Juneteenth Day of Observance, commemorating the day in 1865 when Union troops arrived in Galveston, Texas, to free the remaining enslaved people. He acknowledges the work of abolitionists and activists in advancing the recognition of Juneteenth and emphasizes that making it a Federal holiday is part of his administration's efforts to promote racial equity. President Biden highlights various initiatives undertaken, such as reducing Black child poverty, investing in historically Black colleges and universities, increasing access to affordable homeownership, and promoting diversity in the Federal bench. He also mentions actions taken on marijuana reform, police reform, gun safety, and student debt relief. President Biden calls on Americans to acknowledge and condemn the history of slavery, celebrate Juneteenth, and work towards eradicating systemic racism and inequity.